flist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{refbegin|}}\n* {{citation |last=Gendai |trans-title=Who's who in Modern Japan 2004 |author-link=Nichigai WHO |script-title=ja:\u73fe\u4ee3\u65e5\u672c\u4eba\u540d\u9332 |year=2004 |publisher=Nichigai Associates}}\n* {{citation |last=The Committee for the Printing of Collected Essays Commemorating Dr. Fukui Fumimasa's 70th Birthday and Retirement (\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5\u535a\u58eb\u53e4\u7a00\u30fb\u9000\u8077\u8a18\u5ff5\u8ad6\u96c6\u520a\u884c\u4f1a) |isbn=978-4393112335 |script-title=ja:\u30a2\u30b8\u30a2\u6587\u5316\u306e\u601d\u60f3\u3068\u5100\u793c |trans-title=Thought and Ritual in the Asian Cultural Sphere |language=ja,en|year=2005 |publisher=[[:ja:\u6625\u79cb\u793e|Shunj\u016bsha]]}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://ci.nii.ac.jp/author?q=\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5 CiNii>\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5] (in Japanese)\n* [http://tripitaka.l.u-tokyo.ac.jp/INBUDS/search.php?m=sch&a=&uekey=\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5 INBUDS>\u798f\u4e95\u6587\u96c5] (in Japanese)\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fukui Fumimasa}}\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:1934 births]]\n[[Category:People from Tokyo Metropolis]]\n[[Category:Waseda University alumni]]\n[[Category:Waseda University faculty]]\n[[Category:Japanese sinologists]]\n[[Category:Japanese Buddhist monks]]\n[[Category:Japanese orientalists]]\n[[Category:Japanese Buddhist scholars]]\n", "name_user": "Hanbud", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTranslations by Fukui Fumimasa", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fukui_Fumimasa"}
{"title_page": "Asyla", "text_new": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Asyla''\n| image               = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| composer            = [[Thomas Ad\u00e8s]]\n| catalogue           = [[Opus number|Op]]. 17\n| period              = [[Contemporary classical music]]\n| genre               = [[Orchestra|Orchestral music]]\n| composed            = {{start date|1997}}\n| performed           = {{nowrap|{{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1997|10|1|df=y}}|location=Symphony Hall, Birmingham}}}}\n| publisher           = Faber Music\n| published           = \n| movements           = 4\n| duration            = 22&ndash;25 minutes\n| scoring             = Large orchestra\n| misc                = \n}}\n'''''Asyla''''', [[Opus number|Op]]. 17, is an [[orchestra]]l composition by the British composer [[Thomas Ad\u00e8s]]. It was finished in 1997 and has been performed widely, especially by the British conductor [[Simon Rattle]]. It has been described as a [[symphony]], the third [[Movement (music)|movement]] being its unacknowledged [[scherzo]].<ref name=EMI>{{cite book|last=Porter|first=Andrew|title=Ad\u00e8s: Asyla, u.a. / Rattle \u00b7 Ades (Liner Notes)|year=1999|publisher=EMI Classics}}</ref><ref name=LSO>{{cite web|last=Bailey|first=Patrick|title=Introducing: Ad\u00e8s Asyla|url=http://vimeo.com/74457749|publisher=London Philharmonic Orchestra|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> The third movement is featured in season 4 episode 10 of the Amazon Prime series ''[[Mozart in the Jungle]]''.  \n\n== Composition ==\n\nThe title of the composition is the Latin plural form of [[asylum (antiquity)|asylum]], which here means both ''sanctuary'' and ''madhouse''.<ref name=EMI/><ref name=Barbwire>{{cite book|last=Heninger|first=Barbara|title=Thomas Ad\u00e8s: Asyla (Redwood Orchestra Program|url=http://www.barbwired.com/barbweb/programs/ades_asyla.html|access-date=2014-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417155711/http://www.barbwired.com/barbweb/programs/ades_asyla.html|archive-date=2014-04-17|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was commissioned by the [[John Feeney (newspaper proprietor)|John Feeney Charitable Trust]] and was premiered by the [[City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra]] under the baton of Simon Rattle, in Birmingham's [[Symphony Hall, Birmingham|Symphony Hall]] in October 1997.<ref name=Faber>{{cite web|title=Asyla (1997) by Thomas Ad\u00e8s|url=http://www.fabermusic.com/repertoire/asyla-2510|publisher=Faber Music|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> \n\nThis piece is best known for its third movement, which features [[techno music|techno]]-like traits. Ad\u00e8s himself narrated the compositional process as follows:<ref>{{cite web|title=Asyla (1997) &ndash; Thomas Ad\u00e8s (1971&ndash;) |url=http://www.bartokisdead.com/ades_asyla.htm |work=The Contemporary Classical Music Guide |publisher=Bartokisdead.com |accessdate=17 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418220554/http://www.bartokisdead.com/ades_asyla.htm |archivedate=18 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|So I bought some techno music and listened to it, just quietly, to get the structure rather than blast my head off. I realised that, in techno, you have to repeat things 32 or 64 times. So I tried to orchestrate it one night in my living room, repeating all these figures over and over, on this massive score paper, 30 staves to a page. At 3am, I went to bed and, as I sat there, realised my heart had stopped beating. I thought, 'Christ, I'm having a heart attack'. I rang the hospital and then they sent an ambulance. My heart gradually started again, but very shallowly. The ambulance took me to the Royal Free, where I waited for two hours among other Saturday night casualties. And finally a doctor saw me and said, 'You hyperventilated'. I thought, 'Thank God. It's not my heart, it's just my brain...'|Thomas Ad\u00e8s|The Independent, 27 May 1999<ref name=Independent>{{cite journal|last=Walsh|first=John|title=Arts: A young man in a hurry|journal=The Independent|date=27 May 1999|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/arts-a-young-man-in-a-hurry-1096160.html|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref>}}\n\n''Asyla'' received critical praise and won a [[Royal Philharmonic Society Music Awards|Royal Philharmonic Society Music Award]] in 1997 and the [[Grawemeyer Award for Music Composition]] in 2000. It was eventually published by [[Faber Music]] in 2000.<ref name=Grawemeyer>{{cite web|title=2000\u2013 Thomas Ades |url=http://grawemeyer.org/2000-thomas-ades/}}</ref>\n\n== Analysis ==\n\nThis composition has four movements and takes 22 to 25 minutes to perform. The movement list is as follows:\n{{Ordered list|type=upper-roman\n|[untitled]\n\n|[untitled]\n\n|Ecstasio\n|[untitled]\n}}\n\nIt is scored for a very large orchestra, which, in addition to the most common instruments, should also include two pianos (a grand piano and an upright piano tuned one quarter tone lower), six percussionists playing a large range of instruments, and a [[celesta]].<ref name=Score>{{cite book|last=Ad\u00e8s|first=Thomas|title=Asyla: for large orchestra; op. 17; (1997)|year=1999|publisher=Faber|location=London|isbn=0-571-51863-X|edition=[Partitur], 1. publ}}</ref>\n\nThe piece starts with an untitled movement with [[Cowbell (instrument)|cowbells]] and the flat piano, which is immediately followed by the [[French horn|horn]]s and the high-pitched sound of the strings. The general atmosphere of the movement becomes much more agitated when the rest of the orchestra joins in progressively. The second movement begins abruptly and suddenly changes to a soft melody played by the [[bass oboe]]. Then the strings take over with a style which has been classified by some critics as ''[[Richard Wagner|Wagnerian]]''.<ref name=Barbwire/> The sound starts to dissipate towards the end of the movement, fading out using the highest and lowest registers simultaneously.\n\nThe third movement tries to resemble \"the atmosphere of a massive nightclub with people dancing and taking drugs\". It has a steady rhythm which has been compared to [[Igor Stravinsky|Stravinsky]]'s ''[[The Rite of Spring]]''.<ref name=EMI/> The music here is much more insistent than in the previous movements and is much more vivid and lively. After reaching a climax echoed by the strings, the fourth movement becomes calmer at the beginning, and suddenly turns violent when a tutti chord initiated by the horns bursts towards the end of the piece. ''Asyla'' ends in a quiet but trembling manner.<ref name=Barbwire/><ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web|last=Eriksson|first=Erik|title=Thomas Ad\u00e8s Asyla, for orchestra, Op. 17|url=http://www.allmusic.com/composition/asyla-for-orchestra-op-17-mc0002439139|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of compositions by Thomas Ad\u00e8s]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | author=Venn, Edward | title=Thomas Ad\u00e8s: Asyla | publisher=Routledge | location=London | year=2017 | isbn=978-1-4094-6884-4 }}\n\n{{Thomas Ad\u00e8s}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Thomas Ad\u00e8s]]\n[[Category:1997 compositions]]\n[[Category:Contemporary classical compositions]]\n[[Category:Compositions for symphony orchestra]]\n", "text_old": "{{italic title}}\n{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Asyla''\n| image               = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| composer            = [[Thomas Ad\u00e8s]]\n| catalogue           = [[Opus number|Op]]. 17\n| period              = [[Contemporary classical music]]\n| genre               = [[Orchestra|Orchestral music]]\n| composed            = {{start date|1997}}\n| performed           = {{nowrap|{{Timeline-event|date={{Start date|1997|10|1|df=y}}|location=Symphony Hall, Birmingham}}}}\n| publisher           = Faber Music\n| published           = \n| movements           = 4\n| duration            = 22&ndash;25 minutes\n| scoring             = Large orchestra\n| misc                = \n}}\n'''''Asyla''''', [[Opus number|Op]]. 17, is an [[orchestra]]l composition by the British composer [[Thomas Ad\u00e8s]]. It was finished in 1997 and has been performed widely, especially by the British conductor [[Simon Rattle]]. It has been described as a [[symphony]], the third [[Movement (music)|movement]] being its unacknowledged [[scherzo]].<ref name=EMI>{{cite book|last=Porter|first=Andrew|title=Ad\u00e8s: Asyla, u.a. / Rattle \u00b7 Ades (Liner Notes)|year=1999|publisher=EMI Classics}}</ref><ref name=LSO>{{cite web|last=Bailey|first=Patrick|title=Introducing: Ad\u00e8s Asyla|url=http://vimeo.com/74457749|publisher=London Philharmonic Orchestra|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> The Third Movement Ecstasio is featured in season 4 episode 10 of  the Amazon  Prime series ''[[Mozart in the Jungle]]''.  \n\n== Composition ==\n\nThe title of the composition is the Latin plural form of [[asylum (antiquity)|asylum]], which here means both ''sanctuary'' and ''madhouse''.<ref name=EMI/><ref name=Barbwire>{{cite book|last=Heninger|first=Barbara|title=Thomas Ad\u00e8s: Asyla (Redwood Orchestra Program|url=http://www.barbwired.com/barbweb/programs/ades_asyla.html|access-date=2014-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140417155711/http://www.barbwired.com/barbweb/programs/ades_asyla.html|archive-date=2014-04-17|url-status=dead}}</ref> It was commissioned by the [[John Feeney (newspaper proprietor)|John Feeney Charitable Trust]] and was premiered by the [[City of Birmingham Symphony Orchestra]] under the baton of Simon Rattle, in Birmingham's [[Symphony Hall, Birmingham|Symphony Hall]] in October 1997.<ref name=Faber>{{cite web|title=Asyla (1997) by Thomas Ad\u00e8s|url=http://www.fabermusic.com/repertoire/asyla-2510|publisher=Faber Music|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref> This composition is best known for its third movement, which features [[techno music|techno]]-like traits. Ad\u00e8s himself narrated the compositional process as follows:<ref>{{cite web|title=Asyla (1997) &ndash; Thomas Ad\u00e8s (1971&ndash;) |url=http://www.bartokisdead.com/ades_asyla.htm |work=The Contemporary Classical Music Guide |publisher=Bartokisdead.com |accessdate=17 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140418220554/http://www.bartokisdead.com/ades_asyla.htm |archivedate=18 April 2014 }}</ref>\n\n{{quote|So I bought some techno music and listened to it, just quietly, to get the structure rather than blast my head off. I realised that, in techno, you have to repeat things 32 or 64 times. So I tried to orchestrate it one night in my living room, repeating all these figures over and over, on this massive score paper, 30 staves to a page. At 3am, I went to bed and, as I sat there, realised my heart had stopped beating. I thought, 'Christ, I'm having a heart attack'. I rang the hospital and then they sent an ambulance. My heart gradually started again, but very shallowly. The ambulance took me to the Royal Free, where I waited for two hours among other Saturday night casualties. And finally a doctor saw me and said, 'You hyperventilated'. I thought, 'Thank God. It's not my heart, it's just my brain...'|Thomas Ad\u00e8s|The Independent, 27 May 1999<ref name=Independent>{{cite journal|last=Walsh|first=John|title=Arts: A young man in a hurry|journal=The Independent|date=27 May 1999|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/arts-a-young-man-in-a-hurry-1096160.html|accessdate=21 April 2014}}</ref>}}\n\n''Asyla'' received critical praise and won a [[Royal Philharmonic Society Music Awards|Royal Philharmonic Society Music Award]] in 1997, and the [[Grawemeyer Award for Music Composition]] in 2000. It was eventually published by [[Faber Music]] in 2000.<ref name=Grawemeyer>{{cite web|title=2000\u2013 Thomas Ades |url=http://grawemeyer.org/2000-thomas-ades/}}</ref>\n\n== Analysis ==\n\nThis composition has four movements and takes 22 to 25 minutes to perform. The movement list is as follows:\n{{Ordered list|type=upper-roman\n|[untitled]\n\n|[untitled]\n\n|Ecstasio\n|[untitled]\n}}\n\nIt is scored for a very large orchestra, which, in addition to the most common instruments, should also include two pianos (a grand piano and an upright piano tuned one quarter tone lower), six percussionists playing a large range of instruments, and a [[celesta]].<ref name=Score>{{cite book|last=Ad\u00e8s|first=Thomas|title=Asyla: for large orchestra; op. 17; (1997)|year=1999|publisher=Faber|location=London|isbn=0-571-51863-X|edition=[Partitur], 1. publ}}</ref>\n\nThe piece starts with an untitled movement with [[Cowbell (instrument)|cowbells]] and the flat piano, which is immediately followed by the [[French horn|horn]]s and the high-pitched sound of the strings. The general atmosphere of the movement becomes much more agitated when the rest of the orchestra joins in progressively. The second movement begins abruptly and suddenly changes to a soft melody played by the [[bass oboe]]. Then the strings take over with a style which has been classified by some critics as ''[[Richard Wagner|Wagnerian]]''.<ref name=Barbwire/> The sound starts to dissipate towards the end of the movement, fading out using the highest and lowest registers simultaneously.\n\nThe third movement tries to resemble \"the atmosphere of a massive nightclub with people dancing and taking drugs\". It has a steady rhythm which has been compared to [[Igor Stravinsky|Stravinsky]]'s ''[[The Rite of Spring]]''.<ref name=EMI/> The music here is much more insistent than in the previous movements and is much more vivid and lively. After reaching a climax echoed by the strings, the fourth movement becomes calmer at the beginning, and suddenly turns violent when a tutti chord initiated by the horns bursts towards the end of the piece. ''Asyla'' ends in a quiet but trembling manner.<ref name=Barbwire/><ref name=Allmusic>{{cite web|last=Eriksson|first=Erik|title=Thomas Ad\u00e8s Asyla, for orchestra, Op. 17|url=http://www.allmusic.com/composition/asyla-for-orchestra-op-17-mc0002439139|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=17 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of compositions by Thomas Ad\u00e8s]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book | author=Venn, Edward | title=Thomas Ad\u00e8s: Asyla | publisher=Routledge | location=London | year=2017 | isbn=978-1-4094-6884-4 }}\n\n{{Thomas Ad\u00e8s}}\n\n[[Category:Compositions by Thomas Ad\u00e8s]]\n[[Category:1997 compositions]]\n[[Category:Contemporary classical compositions]]\n[[Category:Compositions for symphony orchestra]]\n", "name_user": "Squandermania", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asyla"}
